. And I said, well what's wrong with my nightdress? Solomon in all his glory was not arrayed in one of these. And I think that tickled her, broke down all her defences. And she - she had a good laugh and of course the boyfriend had a laugh and that was al
ways kept up against me, Solomon in all his glory. Oh dear dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you share a bedroom with your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Yes. After the time my grandmother died, and - and grandfather died. My grandmother died - when she was eighty-two and - and my grand
father - twelve months after. And up 'til that time we had two beds - in the one room, in the room - over this, and - a double and a single bed, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 So you've got three bedrooms and you had six people living here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did it work out then? You had your mother and father in one room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Mother and father had - I'm sorry, not there, mother and father had one bedroom. And grandmother and grandfather had a bedroom. There was - a big fourposter in the room over the living roo
m, which is a bigger you see. And - that was - four poster in that and a single bed. And my brother slept in the single bed. And - my two - two sisters and I had the - they slept - there was only thirteen months difference in those two - girls, and they s
lept in the double bed and I in the single, you see. And mother and father in the other room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 It must have been quite squashed upstairs really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Which room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 We had a bath and - the - the bath that we used to keep - 
it was one of the tin ones and we used to have that in the basement. We had - a - a - our bathroom and toilet now is taken out of the room over the - living room. About - fourteen years ago since we had that done. But up to then we had a toilet - in the b
asement. And - I think we were one of the first to have that done. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How often did you bath in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Every week. And of course you had to wash your neck and face and - and - your - legs if they were dirty summertime, children, you know t
hey're out every - and no stockings on in the summertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have a special bath night for the whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Friday night. Yes. Yes. And there were clean clothes was always - took out and warmed and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You just had clean clothes after bath night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Always had your clean clothes put on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You had a bath once a week?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, Fridays. Friday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Was your mother strict about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, she was very strict on that matter. And - always brought up to have a good old 
wash, you see, every day. And - I'll tell you what because our work was so dirty here even when we were young people - the black}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 leading the stove two or three times a week and that, we - we - we just had to strip off and have a good old wash or else you'd
 have an high water mark around your neck which everyone could see, so - we always had to have a good old wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you ever have clean clothes on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 On a Sunday? Well everything clean was put on, either the Friday night or Saturday morni
ngs. And - Sundays we had our - our best clothes which were kept for best, you see. And - I remember asking mother one - one day in the summertime - it was a lovely - lovely summer and this was a very fine day and I was going Penzance, I was perhaps - sev
enteen or eighteen then, and - I said, mother, shall I put my - my best dress on to go Penzance today? And my mother - looked - very indignant and said in a very stern voice, best? Will never be best any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Where did your family eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What did we eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Where did you eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh we - we ate in our living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You never ate in any other room at any time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Only here, perhaps wintertime we'd have our - our tea down here you see. But for our meals beca
use the cooker - cooking stove then - was in the living room and - it'd be handier to have it there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you sit round the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Or round the fire perhaps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh - always round the table. Never had any - any meals like they
 do now, haphazard, it was always set properly on the table. And - for dinner or tea or supper, that was the - way we lived then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 And your mother had a range out in that sitting room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 She had a - a grate, an old fashioned Cornish grate, everybo
dy - all the houses here - had these Cornish grates until the - the Cornish slabs came in vogue and - and - then - if anybody could afford a Cornish slab they had it. But - this - our living room, the - our grate came at the back of the next door neighbou
r
's fire - place, and we had to have it built out. It's an awkward shaped room you see and it would come right out and the other was part of the room. So we - we couldn't very well have a Cornish Slab. And - I suppose it was just half a dozen houses in the
 village who had a - Cornish Slab. Everyone baked everything. In the - in the big bake}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 houses. There was about eight }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931  bake}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 houses here in the village. And we baked our dinners and our - tarts, fruit tarts and our pies, and our Christmas cakes and fruit cakes, all - everything was baked all the year round in the public oven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Where was the bake}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 house that you used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Near the Keigwen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 That's just round the corner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Here in the road and Saturday mornings you would have a lovely smell in
 this road of saffron cake being baked. They used to - used to have the - gentleman who kept it, Mr Humphries, he would have - two ovens, eight o'clock in the morning would be the first for cakes and bread, and then again at ten for cakes and bread, and i
t would be twelve o'clock dinners or half past - half past ten - somewhere around that time and the dinners and cakes put in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What time did you eat breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What time did we have breakfast? Oh well if we had to go - we had to be at school by ni
ne, the bell, we'd hear the school bell ring about quarter to nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have breakfast with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well - if he was home and my mother when - before she was taken ill, when I was thirteen - but if father hadn't gone to sea he'd be here.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 So it would just be your sisters and your brother and you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Mm. My brother was fishing as well you see. And - he - he would be away just as often as - as - as my father was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you take your mother her breakfast upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh - not until she got sick, when she was sick I took it up for years and years. Up to bed for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What did you have for breakfast, what sort of food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well - our breakfast was - wintertime we would have porridge, and - bread and butter and - and te
a, if we could stay to have it to go to school. And - in summertime we wasn't so fussy over porridge, we'd have - bread and butter and toast and - marmalade or jam, what was going. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have a different meal on a Sunday? Different sort of breakfast, different food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No, well - the only difference we had in - on Sunday was saffron cake. Mother would always make saffron cake Saturday. Bake it Saturdays. Put it to rise Friday nights, and that was a custom of the Cornish folk - they always ma
de up their saffron cake, and - that would be cut up on the plate for - for breakfast, and - we'd have cheese if you - we were always very fond of cheese, my father - and mother and the family, and - suppers and breakfast most often we'd have a - cheese.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What about lunch, did you have lunch as a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
We had our - our lunch - there would be always - dinnertime, we never had it in the evening. Because - on - on the - on the work of the fishermen, they'd be - they would have their dinner and then g
o to sea in the afternoon, they were all night work you see. So they would be out on the fishing ground at - by - three or four o'clock. And - well we'd have something different every day, I can't - if we had - say - the - the - women would - would - pick
l
e the - the fish as the men brought up - perhaps a handful of - mackerel one day or - herring. They would be put into - busses. A busser would be a - a big earthenware pot, that's a Cornish word, and put in coarse salt, made of - a brine all you see and i
t
 would stand for twelve months in that, and - salt pilchards and herring and mackerel would be put - salted down in busses, and we always - the fisher people always had something in their cellars - that they could have for a meal. And - once a week - or m
a
ybe twice we would have perhaps salt mackerel or salt herring, and potatoes boiled in their jackets. They didn't believe in peeling the potatoes then so much then as they do now, they - they always said that the - more nutriment in the skin - under the sk
i
n than anywhere else in the potatoes, so they - if they had fish and potatoes that would be - they would be boiled in their jackets. And - at our little local shop where the Lobster Pot is now we could always have dutch butter. Which was delicious, it was
 a salt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
er butter that our own Cornish butter, and cheaper, a lot cheaper, and for our fish and potato dinner we always had Dutch butter to put - you could use then - this butter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you ever remember having meat? Do you remember eating meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have a lot of meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Oh, and meat was very cheap. We had - more meat then than what we can have now. We got for - with about - with half a crown we'd have a plateful of meat for half a crown, we'd get more that - for half a crown then than what you get now for a pound. Four}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 pence - and three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 pence a pound. Stewing meat and boiling meat at the butchers. And - it was nothing new to hear anyone ask for three or four pennorth of meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of meat dishes did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh we 
- mother varied our - our food you see and - meat was very cheap in those days, so - one day perhaps we would have - well Mondays would be - what was left from Sunday, the meat and - perhaps fresh vegetables or what was left, and - Tuesday we would - mayb
e
 have a - a roast - the potatoes round the - the meat and that. A very nice Cornish dish is - onion and turnip cut up small in the bottom of the tin and potato cut up small and then the potatoes put around, and the meat in the middle, and - a little drop 
o
f water of course, and that'd make a very nice tasty dinner. And there was generally a - tart of some sort and - or a pudding after. Always a pudding, a milk pudding was always made if we had fish of any sort and potatoes. And - then there'd be a - pie, w
i
th meat in it, see, meat pie. And a nice crust on top, and another day would be - soup. And - have the bone, ox bone or something you know and make a nice soup with it. All different sorts of vegetables. And - then there'd be a pasty, and I will say that 
for our fisher}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
wives here they did look after their children and their men and they always contrived to get - a good dinner meal for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What about teatime, what did you eat at teatimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well teatime would be perhaps - a little bit of fish if i
t was going, sometimes see having mackerel see you can - if you went through the village you could smell mackerel roasting in the grid iron. I wish we had a grid ion now, I never see a grid iron, I don't suppose you could buy one anywhere. You could have 
a single grid iron or a double one, you know, where you could put the mackerel in or the herring and - or the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7079132\charrsid3212931 pilchard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
 and - turn the - grid iron over the other side and - roast it on a clear fire and you never had anything so rich, as a mackerel on a grid 
iron, or a herring or a pilchard. Pilchards especially. There's no richer food than those, and - I don't know why - a grid iron now is never made, because we have lovely clear fires here now. And you can never have a - that - fish done that way. I - I sai
d
 yesterday we had - we had mackerel given us, I said oh a - lovely clear fire and - can't we borrow a grid iron from someone. Put it under the grill then of the electric. But it scent the house out, that is - the trouble then and - never done as nice as i
t were put on a fire, a clear fire.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you ever have cakes for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes, well - another Cornish recipe is holteddy cake, which is delicious, it was - very nice, yes and that was always - about two or three times a week we have - and especially 
made for the men to take to sea with them. Always heavy cake or scones, mother was a dab hand for making scones. And you put jam or butter on that and sometimes cream, if there was plenty of money going around you'd have it, always - always - Sundays - yo
u
 had cream in the house and scones. That was a special treat for Sundays. And - there was no fancy living then as it is now, there was no - tins of fruit and Lyons rolls and all that sort of bought stuff that you can get - you know, I - people never had i
t, never - never - wasn't - we had no shops here to sell it, anything like that. No restaurants or no cafes here then and - shops never - never went in for them and - biscuits and fairy cakes, but - never anything - like that to sell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You said earlier that your mother made her own bread, did she make things like jam, or did she bottle fruit or vegetables?
