hing was being - spoken of - about anything in that way, I was always sent out - out of the room. Never anything talked about in this day there is too much talking - spoken of and - I - I know perhaps in those days not enough. But the pendulum have - swun
g - too far the other way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did you get on with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
My father? Oh wonderful. We were good friends. And with my mother, and she was very kind but - on that subject everything was taboo, nothing was spoken about I - I don't know what th
ey they would say if they were alive now and - know so much was - which I don't think really is - good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 We had to - behave ourselves and never answer back. And I don't know what my mother w
ould say or father if they - if the young children - some children - that I've seen and - and heard. But - no, we just had to - do what we were told and there's no question about it. You couldn't argue at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have to behave towards your sisters and your brother in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes. Yes. Although - you know - I was - different - everybody got different disposition, even in the family if you were ten children and - wouldn't be ten alike. And - my two sisters were entirely different, one t
o the other. My elder sister was - very strict, and - brought me up very - you know, firm and that. And - but - I wouldn't answer her for the world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What happened if say one of them hit you, would, you hit back? Or perhaps if another child hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well I don't know - I think if - if any other children did, but - I don't think that - I would have the courage to do it to my sister.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What would your parents say about it if you hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well they wouldn't allow it. They wouldn't like it. 
But - I suppose all children - every generation - do defend themselves if the time come you know. I suppose if any of my friends - had a - bit of argument or fight and that I should be just as good as them at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of people did you think your parents wanted you to be when you got older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What - what children that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of people do you think your parents wanted you to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well they always wanted - for me to - move in - in good - with good companions, and I can reme
mber our schoolmistress at school when we were quite young, Miss Hooper, always saying to us, birds of a feather flock together, now never forget that children. Birds of a feather, and we didn't know what she meant. Until after years we - we tumbled to wh
a
t she meant, you see, I told her one day in the bus, I met her, and I said, I've puzzled your words so often, and she said, oh Nettie my dear, tell me. And - in which - in what way, and I told her - about when we were young - she spoke to us so seriously 
- about - birds of a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4405242\charrsid3212931  theatr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 e flock together, and I said I found out in the - in latter years what you were - what you meant.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of things did your parents think were important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Religion. Reading, knowledge. And religion, and that w
as the - I think the - main thing in life, if you're brought up on that you - won't go far wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Never had any, we never - had it in the family you know, we never - never heard it then in the family. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What happened if perhaps the grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Not in - not interrupt. We had to wait until they - they finished speaking. But - we were allowed to - to have our - opinion and all that, you know, they would listen to us, but we always had to listen first, and always told we must never interrupt.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 If you did something that your parents thought was wrong were you punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, mother would punish me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Always your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Mother would - chas - chasti
se me, I'd have a slap on the leg or slap on me hand, never had a stick in the house. Can never remember her having - me mother using a stick, she had a very heavy hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Would she use it often?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Which - which I've had pretty often, if I didn't come exactly when she called me or - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Your father never hit you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well I was very naughty girl. I - I'm sure I must have been, and he was very annoyed to think that - I had done what I'd done and
 - although at the time I didn't think I was doing any wrong because - we were playing down in the - in Wesley Square - three or four little girls about six or seven years old, and - there was an old man coming by, with a stick you see, and he had a long 
b
eard, and I had always heard him called Jim the Dunkey, that was his nickname I suppose, but I didn't know but what it was his real name. And - of course as he passed he flicked his stick at us in passing you know for us to move out the way, which we didn
'
t like I suppose, and of course we began - well - we little girls - started to calling him Jim the Dunkey, and my dear child, he got so mad - that he chased us. And - we ran in this lady's house and up over the stairs and under the bed. One of the little 
g
irls that lived in the house was playing with us you see. And - eventually the - the lady of the house came - along and - spoke to the old man, kind of consoled him - well my sister was - was mending our - our cousin's nets in the house opposite, and I di
d
n't - I didn't know this. So when eventually I came home up over the - back stairs, my mother and father were in the kitchen, mending nets also, and as soon as I got into the room I had the honniest - smack with my father - across my face which I didn't -
 
I didn't know what it was for you see, I think the shock - of the - slap - was as much as the blow, and to think that he had slapped me, well - eventually I was told - if I ever spoke to anyone or called them by their nicknames which I at the time I didn'
t know was his nickname I was always very careful after that I - but that was the only once that I can remember father - putting his hand to me, I didn't want it anymore either. I always made clear of Jim the Dunkey after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you remember your mother hitting you on any special occasion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No. No, but - no, but - very - hard of course, she would - we were always - a bit afraid of her because - we knew we had to obey her and - but - I never remember having any - any - any - canes with her there, stick or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you think that your mother or your father played the most important part in how you behaved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well mother I think because we had more time with her, in our young life, she was with us more than my father you see. And - that 
was the case in all fisher people here, their - mother had more control - she's with them oftener and more than father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Were you ever taken out to visit the neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh yes, I loved in the evenings, winter evenings, to go out with mother to 
her - cousin's or her sisters houses or friends houses. She'd a special friend in the village - whose husband was also fishing, and - she would have some lovely Quiver magazines - a - monthly magazines called the Quiver you see. And - I knew if mother and
 
her had a chinwag, if they were busy talking that I could have the books to look at the pictures in them. And - read a short article, don't matter it was as long as it's a book you know when I was young. And - so winter evening I used to - I would say to 
m
other sometimes, oh come on mum, let's go out and visit so and so and so and so, it'd either be aunt this or aunt that, or aunt Bella, her friend, and - very important in the wintertime. Not so much in the summer because they were busier - doing the nets 
and different kind of - housework cleaning and etcetera.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your father ever take you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Father? YES? OH my father would take me for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did he take you out visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh no, not very often did I go visiting with father, because - they
 were - if it was fine weather and they were home here fishing it would be - it would be the same mostly until Saturday nights and Sundays nights, and that'd be spent home then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Were you ever taken out shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well Pen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4405242\charrsid3212931 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
ance you mean? Yes. Oh y
es, I have a - turn at Penzance sometimes and - in the summertime if father was in - well - two or three Saturday nights there was a - a party in there on the prom where the - pavilion is now and a big marquee. Kind of variety show and all that you know, 
oh it was wonderful to walk in - of course we had to walk then to Penzance and walk back, and - I thought it was wonderful to - to - go in there, listen to these - variety - show.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 This was just with your father was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh parents, my parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 They both took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. YES.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you remember going out anywhere else with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes. We'd generally go and - we'd go to - Good Friday sometimes if they were - they both wanted to see, and - oh yes, we'd generally go and - we went up - 
we had a cousin living in Tringoltho then, St Lytham then, St Lytham Parish, they were farmers on Tregoltho Farm and - would be - perhaps the summertime we'd - we'd go up to St Lytham which is eight miles - there and it was Saturday afternoon we went walk
 away in there and - stay for the weekend you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you ever have holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Not very often. Never had a half holiday, we didn't have much holidays in those days, we'd have - two weeks in the summer, two or three weeks in the summer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You went away then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No. No, spend it here. Well - I - I say - spend it here. I meant go up to this to the farm. Come down the - they would supply the chops with butter here and eggs and - and - if Mr Austin came in and I was here you know and - not very 
well he would say, throw her up in the cart Lizzie and - a few days in St Leonard will do me all the world of good and that was - a lovely little bit of a holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of things would you do when you were up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh play with the childre
n in the moor - in the - the movie and the hayricks and - that were and - collect the eggs and bring them in and - oh - and pick black-berries or primroses, around the edges. Marvellous. Lovely holidays then up there. Sometimes mother would go with me and
 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did you spend Saturdays in those days when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well Saturdays - when we were young in the summertime - we would be - mother would say go down Pawr and play. Well we never questioned - where Pawr - we - we knew where the Pawr wa
s but we didn't question the funny name - of being called the Pawr. But the pawr apparently is an old Cornish word for harbour, and - the - old name of Mousehole was Pawrennis. Porthenys, and Port was the harbour and Enys was the island. And - so we would
 spend our Saturday mornings in the harbour, playing, making the - having shops on one of the big flat rocks down there. Picking up the sea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4405242\charrsid3212931 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 wood for butter and - and big - big round stones for bread and you see we used - we passed away and washing our feet 
- lagging as we used to call it. And that was Saturday mornings, well then we would be called up for dinner and - always washed a good old wash after - after playing down the harbour we'd have a good wash after dinner and have our clothes changed. All the
 
- clothes changed Saturday afternoons and if we had any pocket money at all it was given to us then. Sometimes we had much, sometimes we had little, sometimes nothing at all, but - we had the grace and the knowledge not to make a fuss even if we didn't ha
ve anything. And - that was - the Saturday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What about Sundays, were you allowed to play on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No. No. We always knew from time - we started life we never played Sundays. I had a doll, a wood doll - when I was young and - I was never allow
ed to play with my doll on Sundays, on Sunday mornings. But I could have a book to read, you see, that was not - never barred from me. And - of that I'm very glad but - from earliest remembrances - after breakfast and that we went to chapel, and my father
 - he always went Sunday mornings and mother stayed here of course to cook the dinner and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What did they feel about work on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh, terrible. Nothing was allowed to be done, but my mother wasn't like her mother. Her mother - mother wo
uld always have the things washed up, the - the - plates and saucers, cups and saucers were always washed on a Sunday, but that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your mother go to chapel on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Your father went in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 He always went in 
the morning with me and - mother and father in the evening. Always went in the evening. And my - two sisters they were - but my - eldest sister and brother was always in the choir in my remembrances and - I went - after - when I was eleven I went in the c
hoir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your sisters go? Did your sisters and brothers go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Oh always, yes. My brother was in the choir, my eldest sister until she was married and - he went, he was after until he went to America. And - he was over thirty when he went to America, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes. We went at - we went to class Sunday mornings, there was a - a lady who had a - young woman's class, a girls class for small and young woman and we went to that ten o'clock, had our breakfast 
and go out to the class, and after the class I go - I go into chapel - which commenced eleven. And of course - that ended about quarter past, half past twelve then, and they'd come in and have dinner, and had a wash - of course we changed to have your din
n
er, you would never sit down and have your dinner with your - best clothes on, that was customary to take off your things as soon as you came in from chapel. And that was done and then of course after we had our dinner we changed and put on our best cloth
es again and we went to Sunday school. And - came in half past three and - had a read of the book and then - tea, and - changed again for chapel in the evening, six o'clock service.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You went in the evening as well did you?
