e - the neighbours, they'd had - and afterwards - after this happened they - had lost of money, in fact he was a millionaire. He had - he had permission of the harbour to put a wall - and a gate, to come into that part of the wharf then, which was all ope
n
 before you see. Money could speak all languages in those days, more so than now. Neighbours - the neighbours then - to show their indignation after the wall had been built to keep everybody out - and the fisher people had always gone in that little wharf
 
to watch the boat coming in at nights you see, and they took it as a great affront to think these Americans could come here and do a thing like that and turn me off from a place where my parents had always lived, and - so - they burnt a - an effigy - a ma
