Oh, well - perhaps we had had a little bit of a fight or - some other - girl or - had kicked anybody or somebody had kicked us and - our - or took our - our hat away and 
hid our hat and - which was all sorts and kinds of things - were done like that with a mixed school, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of punishments did you get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Get a slap you know, if you - if you were late in the mornings. The headmaster at that time was Mr B
irch. He was very strict, and if we were late he - we would have a - a - smack across our head, he was very fond of giving you a smack across your head at which we always hated. And our two ears would be - sore afterwards you know with his hand. So - I'm 
afraid I was late - pretty often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Were the girls punished the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes. Called out in front of the school. And - made to look very small. See? If you didn't do the right thing or - if you had been misbehaving, speaking was one of the
 things that we weren't allowed to do in school, I've been surprised - in recent years to - to go to schools and - and find out how the children - walk about the school and - and talk to one another, different to what we were ever allowed. If we wanted a 
pencil - or a pen or a rubber we - had to put our hands up, and ask. See? But I think they now go out and take them and - comeback again, they seem to be walking around all the time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Were your parents interested in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, very much. Very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes, and if I - if I had been kept in - for speaking - which is one of the things we were never allowed to do - my mother would be very indignant. About it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Would they ever go up to the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 I don't think she ever went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
But - no, father was always at sea or if he was home you know, he - I don't think they ever took up to make any - to send up notes or anything. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did they ever meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
And my husband - who was three years older than me, he was kept in one day for something and - his mother went after - his dinner was ready and going cold and he - hadn't been told to go home, he was kept in and - half past twelve ca
me and - his mother went up and - the teacher was there as well with him and - she ordered my husband out, she ordered him out. And - said, your dinner is prepared and - spoiling, so now come home and - eat what's left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your parents ever meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 To talk about you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes, because - the - the lady teacher we had - who I had after - when I got out in to the big room, was - Emmeline Curnow, and - funnily enough I had a letter from her - her daughter last week from
 New Zealand, and - she was - well kind of related to my parents, my mother and would come down very often, but I think the only re - only - mother would ask her how I behaved, and did I give her any trouble, the only excuse - only thing she would say was
 that I talked too much, I suppose I'm still doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 All the children from the village went to the school did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Yes. Well - I - yes, two or three, I don't know for why, I never knew how, but - but - three or four children from Mouseh
ole went to Pool school. I don't know what reason they had to attend Pool but they would always - pass us up you know in the lane when we were going to school. One family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do-you remember the teachers singling out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well we always - we always - felt that - the very - brilliant scholars - was - fawned on more than the children who were - who were backward. I never think the teachers are - have got the patience for backward children - as they hav
e for those who can - especially in - arithmetic, you know, some children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
s brains were quicker than others - for arithmetic, and - I think as a matter of fact that that was my weak subject. I could never grasp it so quickly as - perhaps the - one or two o
f the other children. But - as soon as the other - the sharper children had got hold of the - mathematics was doing that, then they went on to a higher grade instead of putting more time - on - what they were - teaching us you see. Because one or two had 
- had got it quicker than the others, then the others had to - manage the best they could, which in - thinking about things after I thought that - we hardly had a - fair chance.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you remember any gangs at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh yes. Yes. There were gangs and - I suppose in every - school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you remember children being left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Some children - were I think, if you were favour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 tes you know you had - more opportunity to - get into things. If you were good at singing or - reciting and things like that, you had more chance in concerts of taking part, than those who hadn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you just go to this one school or did you go on to another school afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No, I never went anywhere else, only there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Thirteen. Thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Would you have stayed longer if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well I don't think so, no, I felt very happy - that I came home, and - I will say that I'm - I am sure I have - learnt more or - learnt myself more since I finished school than I did - when I went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you ever take part in any part time education after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you ever go to evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Wel
l I - I - if I had the chance of - of learning more I suppose I should have had. It would have been for my benefit. But I think when you're thirteen you didn't see - didn't think on those things, and my mother was very very ill, and at that time I was ver
y worried and upset, we didn't think that she would live. And - because I could stay home, you see, and be here - helping I was happier than if I had - kept in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931 Do you think you benefi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 ted from attending school in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Sure did, it
 gave me a love of - of knowing about - other places, the - geography and - I loved geography lessons and history. And - reading, I was always the - the best one - for reading in the class, I used - my name would be called out for reading when the examine
 - when the examination was and - the gentleman came who - would be - well - he was supposed to be the examiner - as in different subjects you see, and - so often - every year they would come and I'd be always called out to read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No, no, no means of getting money. I would have my - my jobs given me, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 This is at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, before I left school at thirteen I would have - jobs, Friday
 afternoons would be cleaning the brick things of - the brickwork down with the knives, to clean on the brick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
boarded, with brick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You had no paid work though did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No paid work, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have a full time job after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes, I - went - when I was fourteen in February month, my father got a job for me at Higher Kemyel which is - nearly three miles from here, and - to bunch the flowers, the workmen would pick the flowers in the meadows, and then - we girls would bunch t
hem. For the - for the grand sum of three ha'pence an hour. That was the first year, and - the flowers would last say perhaps about - two or three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 months. And then - the next year - it would be tuppence ha'penny, but the wages never rose, from tuppence ha'penny and hour. Just fancy now - anybody walking nearly three mile - for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 ha'pence an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Was that the only sort of job you did?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 When I was - when I was - no, I - I worked in the fish cellar when I was - fourteen. In the winter, that's a
 winter job. Now those things were the only thing to do in the village. There was no factories, there were no factories and there was only out to work by the day - or in the fish cellar, in the pilchard season and the flower season would be - from January
 perhaps 'til Easter, and the fish cellar would be from - October up to Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What things did you do in the fish cellar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Packed. Packed the pilchards in casks. See? Very cold job in the winter time and especially when you put your hand in th
e basket first thing in the morning. That was the same rate of wage. Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
ha'pence an hour for the first year, and then - tuppence ha'penny for the second - for - ever after that was tuppence ha'penny an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of hours did you work while you were doing these jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 We worked from nine - until twelve. Then came home and had our dinner, and - from one o'clock until six in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 This is both in the flowers and in the fish cellar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. That was - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You stayed at home after you left school didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Looking after your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes, looked after my mother in between times, did the housework before I went up for the flowers and - what I couldn't do before I went I did after I came home and the same for the - fish cellar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did starting work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No. Not at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What about with your brother and your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 My - my brother was - married and - my two sisters and my brother were married the same year. When I was fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 So you were starting work as they left home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. So I had to - I was here and then of course my brother went to America.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you spend Sunday any differently when you were working from before you started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No. I rose still at the same time Sunday mornings and - and - had breakfast and went out to my class and - and then on to the church for my - morning service. And didn't make a bit of difference - when I commenced to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Oh yes. Yes, great politician I thought I was. Anyway - I - I put my whole heart into politics the same as I did in - in anything else, in my work and - in - religious matters, and do you know my - my great friend, who 
was - much older than I always said to me, politics, Nettie, and religion always go together. And I found that out, I found that to be true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You said earlier on how you spent your spare time while you were at school, did your spare time activities cha
nge in any way when you were working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No. No. There was - you mean as regards the - practicing, the concerts, the singing. Yes. Always - always the - always something on, Wesley Guild when I got older and - getting up - meetings for that every week a
nd playing, playing the piano and - I - I can't see that I - I'm - had much of that time when I was young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Only for practicing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Where was that to, the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well different places, would be for the mal
e voice sometimes and - for different things in the society. And - Band of Hope and - and children coming here practicing and - individual you know coming here to practice solos, my mother would get fed up sometimes, you've always got - always got crowds 
of people coming in practicing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Did you find that working helped you make any new friends, boys or girls or did you find that your friends were still the same when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh well we would alter sometimes or - I think we used to have 
bits of squabbles you know with our friends and - change around, occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 But did you actually enlarge your horizons as far as friends were concerned?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. Yes I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did you meet your new friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well through 
the church and - through the - through politics. Politics I met - quite a few. That enlarged my mind and different subjects, and - Mr Edwin Tregenser was - a very very - intellectual person and - I was about - not quite good friends with her, and differen
t friends I made - as I got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you ever bring them home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Yes. We could always bring our friends here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Yes I did, I have a - a very special friend whom I met who I - got -
 friendly with when I was perhaps seventeen or eighteen, through being in the choir. And we were great friends up to the time that she - she got married and went to America. And - I spent a fortnight with her when we went out about ten years ago. Great fr
iends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you go anywhere special with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No, I couldn't because she was in - her mother was an invalid, and she had to look after her mother just like I did you see. I think that's the reason we had this close tie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did they want to know where you were when you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes. Yes. And - sometimes I'd be twelve o'clock before I'd come home, some of my friends, and my mother would be worried to death and saying - whatever
 in the world's the attraction up there. And the attraction was something I was never allowed to do home, and that was have a game of cards. And that was taboo but - never allowed in this house you see, and you - you know, I've thought lots of times if yo
u
 try to keep children from something they will in - eventually - try it out you see, and - Eva was a - she was a shut in you see like me but - she had sisters - who were home, not married, and - nieces and nephews coming to the house and she taught me whi
st - the game of whist. Well of course I was very interested in whist, never played for money in my life, never have yet, but I loved the game of whist. And - so I wouldn't dare tell my mother what we done.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What time was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 This was after I was married I'd be up there perhaps by twelve you know and mother could never think why I wanted -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Before you were married did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, mother always
 wanted - nine - nine o'clock, if we were after nine I had to give an account of myself, and where I'd been and who I'd been with. They were very strict on if you were out in the night. They never thought that we - it was nice for a young woman to be out 
late. Of course now this days a different day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 When were you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 I was married in - at - May month, third of May, 1917. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Twenty-three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How long had you known your husband before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well I'd known him all my life because he was born here in the same village - but we went together about four years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did you meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 I - I think we met first at the - our gala, or Park as we called it. And - kept friends ever - well from 
that. But - he was - he went at that time - on Lord Leave's yacht, he was - what we call a yachtsman, and these millionaires that owned these yachts would send to Cornwall for their - crews, they always depended on the Cornish fishermen, well thought that
 
they would be - up in the knowledge of - navigation and that and - so the - most of the - yachts were manned by Cornish crews, and - my young man at that time would be - yachting. So - we went together for a few months and then the time was up for him to 
g
o - on the yachts and they would practically be away all the summer months. And that would be the - every - every year the same thing and then they would go away in the wintertime to the Mediterranean, for the gentry, so I didn't see much of him, and - ne
ver home to take me to any of the - outings or galas or anything in the summertime. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Can you remember the first time you met his parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well I always knew his parents you see, yes. And - always - although - his parents - parents lived in 
the upper part of the village and we lived down town. But - I knew them very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What kind of home did he come from, was it similar to yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, they were - his parents - his father was a fisherman, and - lived in one of the cottages here in
 Mousehole. Had the same upbringing, went to the same school. Although he was three years older I didn't know - very much about him when I was - attending school see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did he go to chapel or to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. Chapel, Methodist, but they attended the other Methodist church in the village. And - at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 As time went on were you treated as one of the family before you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, always very good to me, no trouble at all - Jack's mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Would, they let you talk together by yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Oh yes. Yes, we always visited. Jack was the eldest you see of the family. And - he was the elder - elder of - four brothers and two sisters, there were five brothers altogether and two sisters. So - they all looked up to Jack when he - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 When did you actually have time to talk together at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well we didn't have much time in the home to talk together, my parents would be here you see and - his parents and the other children, being a big family - we got - if we went f
or a walk together that was the only - free time we had for - having anything - to converse about or - talk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did you get on with your parents in law after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you see very much of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 My parents, well I lived here -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Your parents in law?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh - yes, practically nearly every day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you help them with old jobs and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 I did. Yes, I always helped as much as I could, I used to - I was always very handy with my - hands and pape
ring a room or painting or - doing ce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
ngs and I - and I think all the - young women in the village you know could always keep our houses clean and - never hired to have any rooms papered or painted, and - it - granny Pender wanted a hand - to clean a room, I was always available to help.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What did you call your parents in law before you were married and did you call them anything different after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well I'm afraid - up to the time I was married I was Mrs Pender, and Mr Pender, but
 after the children were born it was Grandma Pender, I can't remember what I called her after I was married at first, I suppose I was - Mrs Pender I think. But - being my mother was alive and father I couldn't very well call her mother, and - after the ch
ildren - after - I was - married thirteen months when - our first child was born, and - I think for about - after that it was always grandmother and grandfather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Presumably your husband knew your parents before you were married just as well as you knew his parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, yes, we all knew - one and the other here in the village then, of course not now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Was he the first boy that you brought home for them to meet, as a boyfriend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. The first one that came in. Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did they ever warn you off certain others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Or encourage you to go out with somebody specific?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Yes. I - been put off - two or three chaps before that. And I'm afraid that no one was ever good enough - in their eyes, for their daughter, and - I thi
nk that by - hearing my sisters - telling me after they were the same. They had always - obstacles put in the way as soon as they went with anyone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your parents know his parents before you started courting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes, yes, everyone knew one and the other here in the village, yes. Especially the fisher folk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How would they know each other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well by being - in the - in this little village you see, the small village and everyone knew one another, and - they knew the different families and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did they see very much of each other, the two sets of parents after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well - yes, yes, they always - Grandma Pender always came down, of course my mother couldn't visit - up there because she was - invalid you see, didn't go out
 a lot, only around the door perhaps, but - my mother-in-law and father-in-law came - my father-in-law died - very young, he was only fifty-four when he died. And then Grandma Pender would come down most evenings and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What sort of things would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Oh well they would just sit and talk about what happened in the day and - and the other members of the family, what was happening to them and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Generally gossiping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Going back to the time when you first started courting can yo
u tell me how often you saw each other? What sort of things did you - used to do together at that time? Did this change as time went on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No - well I - I think we would see each other perhaps about - three or four evenings a week, not every evening. I
 used to have - things to do in the house and there would be practicing different meeting - different evenings and I don't know that I - I - I saw Jack so often as that, unless he came and waited for the practice to be over and - but even so we couldn't g
o for much walks because I had to be in early, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 So what would you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Come home then, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 What would you do when you were together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Go for a walk. We went - people used to go for country walks then all around and - have a talk on
 what was happening and what the news was and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did your relationship change at all as you got nearer to being married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No, all the same.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you carry on going out in groups of friends while you were courting, did you still see all your friends, did you go out in groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Well - in the war years, when the men were away we went out in groups - our girlfriends then kept company, but - as regards - Jack and I in walking around you know having a nice country walk or sometimes - of a Satur
day evening we'd go Penzance and pictures or - maybe two evenings a week but that'd be all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 You didn't ever go out in a foursome?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Oh yes, no - if we went off for the day somewhere maybe we went foursome - another girlfriend and - his brother was
 engaged to - my cousin, and - if they were home, from yachting or from the war years - that they happened to be home together we would go off then, two couples.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 And during the war years you went out with your girlfriends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did you go on any holidays together during your courtship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Never had a holiday together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Do you remember a moment when you actually decided to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Yes. I - I remember that very well, because there was a row. A row from my parents - as a matte
r of fact my brother-in-law had been drowned - in a mine sweeper - in - February, and - his wife had then had a little baby about a month before that, she had - she was left with four boys, and a baby a month old you see, this happened in May, and - we ha
d
 been in with her, my mother and father and I had been in there sleeping and all that see, and - she was in a lot of trouble and - these - and her children - and - Jack had been in Africa - about fourteen months after - he was taken off the yacht, the war
 
was declared while - exactly as they came home from the Mediterranean and they were dismantling the yacht when - the war started and he had - they couldn't come home to - even had their Naval Reserve clothes, he was in the Naval Reserve, and - he was neve
r
 allowed to come home, he had to have his clothes sent on to him. And - sent to Portsmouth. So - they were sent away then, he'd been away then fourteen or fifteen months yachting, and - in the Miranda, Lord Leave's yacht and then - he was put on the Kinto
n
's Castle - which was a - was an African liner and - she was armed, guns put on her, and he was in Africa about - nearly eighteen months you see. And - that - my - my brother-in-law was drowned - while he was in Africa. Of course I slept with my sister at
 
the time that she had her trouble and - I was very upset and worried with her being so - ill, and this little family to help to look after. And I got run down myself, so Jack came home from Africa at that time and had leave. Had leave from the Monday, cam
e home Monday night until the Sunday morning, he had to go back - and - when he came home and saw I was looking so - ill, he - decided he was going to get married you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did either of you actually say, will you marry me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 No, he said - this nig
ht when he came you know he said, look I'm going to get the licence tomorrow. So I said, oh for goodness sake don't get that, I'll never be allowed to get married. And - he said, well if I don't marry you soon I shall have nothing to marry. And - with all
 
I said to him about not getting it and I said my mother and father would be very annoyed about it - anyway he was insistent of - of getting this license and getting this license and - I was working with the flowers at the time, here in the village, I got 
a
 job then - the few years before that here in the village, and in between times looking after my sister and my mother had been in there I - was there that day and - coming home from work he called me - I passed by his parents, and he was waiting for me yo
u see and he said I've been up Penzance and got the licence and then we're getting married at Thursday morning. I had that bombshell then to tell my parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Were you surprised that he wanted to marry you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Well he was determined you see, he was - very determined chap, and - anyway -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 Did he actually ask your parents permission?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
No. No we didn't. I don't think that - they troubled about that very much as long as the girl gave her consent and - in those days. Anyway -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6429687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 How did your parents react?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2506258 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 
Oh very very bad about it. They didn't like it. They thought that - I was getting married to - bring more trouble on them. Anyway, we were married and - Thursday morning in Chapel Street in Penzance. And - if you'd like to hear the r
emainder of it - we went - we - there was no motor cars in those days you see and the village - boasted of a carriage and pair, you know, we could always have a carriage to take you anywhere, so that was always in demand for weddings, and - with - my - bo
y
friend, he went up and spoke to the carriage you see to come and collect me at Thursday morning and we were being married in Chapel Street, and - we hadn't time for a honeymoon - in those days, so we went for a drive, we went for a ride to Lands End, and 
-
 we went to the - Lands End Hotel, we'd been heavily rationed now in the war years, the first world war was heavily rationed, no potatoes - for - two years I suppose, and not much else, and we were looking forward to having a nice dinner at the Lands End 
H
otel, anyway Jack ordered up dinner, his - his brother and my cousin, and his sister also went that day, and - he ordered up a - a nice - smash up dinner you see, and - when he came back from ordering - you should have seen our faces. He said that the - h
otel proprietor had told him that - all we could have would be a boiled egg. And only one each. So that was our - our wedding day dinner, a boiled egg. We generally have a boiled egg every - anniversary the third of May. And - our hearts went down in our}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6365406\charrsid3212931  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14897221\charrsid3212931 bo
ots. Anyway we had to make the best of that, and bread and butter, I don't know there was anything else, I can't remember that part of it, but I can't remember the disappointment we had, and - then I had a cousin who was a school master in Sennan at the t
i
me, and - Sennan is just - a mile from Lands End, so he had - had written me a card and told me to come up and - have tea with - come and have tea with them. My mother had written and - and let them know you see, so - we went there for our tea and they ha
d
 a nice tea - waiting for us. And - the Satur - the Sunday morning we walked to Penzance, my husband had to go back then on the early train to Cardiff, to meet the ship. And he went - we - we walked in to Penzance on the Sunday morning - we met the minist
e
r who had married us walking to Newlyn to take the service in Newlyn chapel, he recognised us and - came across to where we were and wished us - or wished my husband all the best of luck. The Reverend Alfred Hold, and - then we went in and he caught the t
r
ain and went and then I walked home. And - I had a - a - few lines from him the Tuesday morning to say that his ship had sailed and gone, and the guns were taken off - this - the ship had gone and he had had to go on a smaller boat with another gun, he wa
s
 a gunner, and he couldn't tell me where you see. So I never heard any more from him for three months. So my mother always - kept on saying to me - well you'll never see your husband any more. See? And at the end of three months I had a letter from Scotla
n
d, they'd been - up in Archagnel, and they'd been snowed in, see, and he couldn't receive any mail, and he couldn't send any mail - he - he would write but I - I had them all in a heap afterwards you see. So that was our married life. Not very - enthralli
ng was it. Not a very good start was it? No. I think I had lots of disappointments - in the early part of my life that - it got me accustomed to bearing a lot since. Mm hm.
